I2C Protocol (Inter-Integrated Circuit)
I2C is a two-wire serial communication protocol used to connect a microcontroller (such as an Arduino or ESP32) with multiple sensors and devices in IoT systems. It allows several devices to communicate over the same two wires, reducing wiring complexity.
SDA and SCL Lines
●	SDA (Serial Data): Carries the data between the master and slave devices.
●	SCL (Serial Clock): Carries the clock signal generated by the master to synchronize data transfer.
How I2C Addressing Works
Each I2C device has a unique address (typically a 7-bit address). The master sends the address of the desired device on the I2C bus, and only the device with the matching address responds while the others ignore the communication. This allows multiple sensors to share the same SDA and SCL lines.
Three Common IoT Sensors That Use I2C
1.	BMP280 (Pressure & Temperature)
2.	BME280 (Temperature, Humidity & Pressure)
3.	MPU6050 (Motion sensor)

